1. Executive Summary

The target system was found to be running an exposed MariaDB database service. Due to a common deployment misconfiguration, the database allowed administrative (root) access without requiring a password. By directly interacting with the service via the command-line interface (CLI), internal tables were enumerated, leading to the successful retrieval of a hidden flag.
2. Technical Enumeration

An initial scan using nmap identified a single points of entry:

    Port 3306/TCP: Running MySQL 5.5.5-10.3.27-MariaDB.

MySQL and MariaDB are relational database management systems (RDBMS) used to store organized data in tables, rows, and columns.
3. Exploitation & Foothold

Access was gained by leveraging a passwordless login vulnerability on the root account. Using the MySQL CLI client, the following command was used to establish a connection:
mysql -h <target_ip> -u root
4. Database Navigation and Data Extraction

Once connected, the database was navigated using standard SQL queries. It is critical to note that every command in the MySQL shell must be terminated with a semicolon (;) to execute.
Step	Command	Result
Enumerate Databases	SHOW databases;	Identified a non-standard database named htb.
Select Database	USE htb;	Switched the active context to the htb database.
Enumerate Tables	SHOW tables;	Found two tables: config and users.
Extract Data	SELECT * FROM config;	Displayed all rows, revealing the system flag.
5. Conclusion

The vulnerability in this system stemmed from an intentional or accidental misconfiguration where the root user was left without a password during the deployment stage. This allowed an attacker to bypass the web application entirely and "talk" directly to the SQL service, gaining full access to all stored data.
